<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880907-0058 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief: Union Texas Petroleum Holdings </HL><SO> </SO><CO> UTH </CO><TEXT>   Union Texas Petroleum Holdings Inc., Houston, said a unit received $127.8 million from its insurers for property damage on the Piper Alpha oil platform, which exploded in the North Sea in July.    The unit, Union Texas Petroleum Ltd., has a 20% interest in the platform. The payment represents $137.8 million of physical damage coverage, less a $10 million aggregate deductible.    Union Texas, the nation's largest independent oil company, also has $275 million, or 36 months, whichever occurs first, of business interruption coverage and $70 million of well control and redrilling coverage, as well as third-party liability pollution and platform removal coverage.    Occidental Petroleum Corp. was operator of the platform. </TEXT></DOC>